article.headline: Seattle reins in Augustus, Storms back to beat Lynx
article.linkText: Seattle reins in Augustus, Storms back to beat Lynx
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Seattle coach Anne Donovan wanted her players
to hold off Minnesota star Seimone Augustus.

While Augustus scored 16 points in the third quarter, the WNBA's
second-leading scorer was held to 24 for the game as the Storm used
a 19-0 second-half run on Saturday night to defeat the Lynx 92-75.

"We did (a good job), I think, in the first half of getting the
ball out of her hands," Donovan said. Saturday's effort against
Augustus was an improvement from two weeks ago, when she scored 32
points against Seattle.

The Storm's inside combo of Lauren Jackson and Janell Burse
combined for 49 points on 18-of-21 shooting while Sue Bird set a
franchise record with 14 assists, which was also a WNBA season
high.

"When they're on like that, (Jackson and Burse) are the best
post players in the league," Donovan said. "Sue recognized it,
and 14 assists later, we rode their backs."

Burse had a season-high 24 points on 9-of-11 shooting while
Jackson was 9-of-10 for 25 points.

Jackson, who was scoreless for 17 1/2 minutes, played 27 minutes
in Donovan's scaled-back approach to resting her star player.
Jackson grabbed 10 rebounds for Seattle (10-8) after having sat out
the previous game because of a stress fracture in her left shin.

"Lauren never surprises me anymore," Donovan said.

Augustus, the WNBA's top draft pick, was 8-of-18 from the field
for Minnesota (5-11). The Lynx have lost five straight games and
seven of their last eight.

Seattle was coming off an emotional win over Los Angeles on
Wednesday in which it beat the West's top team without Jackson.
Against Minnesota, the Storm shot a season-high 55 percent from the
field, posting a franchise-record 32-point quarter in the fourth,
and making all 21 of its free throws.

Minnesota, despite a 32-point third quarter, shot 39 percent
from the field.

Augustus rebounded from her 1-of-8 showing in the first half to
help the Lynx rally from a 15-point deficit. With a 20-6 run during
an 8 1/2-minute stretch spanning the second and third quarters,
Minnesota cut the Storm lead to a point.

Minnesota, which took its first lead of the game at 49-48, saw
its last lead at 64-62. The ensuing 19-0 Seattle run happened in
just 4 1/2 minutes.

"We missed easy baskets, had crucial turnovers and they
capitalized," Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio said.

Storm guard Betty Lennox, guarded closely by Augustus and
limited to 22 minutes due to in part to foul trouble, was held to
four points after scoring 27 on Wednesday.
